### Top recurring questions you ask when troubleshooting

* **Why is my app ‚Äúfailing to respond‚Äù on Railway?**
  This is often a port binding or health‚Äëcheck issue. Ensure your server listens on `0.0.0.0` and reads `process.env.PORT` (or `$PORT` for Python), and that a `/api/health` endpoint returns 200 OK„Äê426‚Ä†source„Äë„Äê431‚Ä†source„Äë.

* **Health checks fail after deployment ‚Äì what should the endpoint return?**
  A simple JSON response at `/api/health` with status 200 is sufficient. Don‚Äôt forget to configure this path in `railpack.json` or the Railway settings„Äê426‚Ä†source„Äë.

* **Frontend and backend work locally but break on Railway ‚Äì what now?**
  Replace any hard‚Äëcoded `localhost` URLs with Railway domain references (public and private) so services talk over the proper network„Äê426‚Ä†source„Äë.

* **CORS errors appear in production ‚Äì how do I fix them?**
  Set CORS middleware to allow your production frontend URL and `credentials: true`. Avoid using `*` in production„Äê426‚Ä†source„Äë.

* **WebSockets connect locally but not in prod ‚Äì what am I missing?**
  Use `wss://` for secure origins and ensure your server‚Äôs CORS/WS configuration allows the deployed domain„Äê426‚Ä†source„Äë.

* **Why does my Nixpacks or Docker build fail?**
  Conflicting build files (Dockerfile, railpack.json, railway.toml) and hard‚Äëcoded ports are common culprits. Pick one build method, remove competing configs, expose the dynamic `PORT`, and check the start command„Äê426‚Ä†source„Äë.

